clarify_b:
Eliza emailed me after missing class. I have pasted the text below. We advised her mid-semester that is not an appropriate way to communicate to professors and the tone of the email was unprofessional. I wanted to make you aware of what her response to her action of oversleeping. Please contact me with any questions. Professor Tiffany Warford. 

On Feb 19, 2015, at 7:24 PM, "Eliza F Hare" <efhare@my.okcu.edu> wrote:

 Mrs. Warford,
 
I am aware that you have to abide by the laws of the Dance School, but I feel the need to explain my case.
 
I am not a dance major.  I am an acting major who is required to take a certain amount of dance credits in order to graduate.  Thus I do not see why those of us who are not making a career in dance should be forced to uphold the same strict disciplines as those who are actual dance students.  Also I know the rules of the Dance School.  I am aware of the consequences of an unexcused absence and the requirements to fix an excused absence.  That is why I told myself at the beginning of my freshman semester that I would NEVER miss a dance class.  Last week I was miserably sick.  I had some Hell-spawned version of bronchitis and a fever, and honestly I could not function properly.  On top of this misery I was also in tech week for a show.  But instead of sleeping and trying to be as rested as possible for my rehearsals, I showed up to dance class on time both days and did sit writes.  Do you honestly think that I would drag my wheezing body out of bed to write 2 essays on a tap class and then plan to not show up to class a week later?  

The night before the day in question was extremely busy.  I had a sorority event till 9:00pm and then Spring-sing practice till 11pm or later.  When I got back to my dorm other unforeseen events happened that preventing me from sleeping.  I did not mean to over sleep.  Obviously, God knew that my body needed rest more than a tap class that morning.  Thus again, I don't understand why my grade has to be dropped, just because I needed a morning to be human.  It happens.  The Dance School has the right to ignore this fact, but they can't change it.  

I know that the dance faculty put these strict rules in place in order to train students to be disciplined and to always be prepared and present for auditions and such.  I understand that.  But what the dance faculty needs to understand is that THIS is not an audition.  THIS is a dance class that we have no actual interest in taking.  We are only here for a credit.  If I knew I had an audition at 10 in the morning I would not have gone to the AXO event or spring sing practice, but this is college.  This is a safe place where students learn how to do things correctly by making mistakes.  This particular situation is not one of those lessons.  What I'm learning from this experience is that the Ann Lacy School of American Dance and Arts Management has the right to strip you of your 4.0 GPA if technology malfunctions or you show any evidence of being a human.  

I'm sorry for my humanity.  I really am.  Please forgive me for my human condition and if you can  PLEASE find a way to allow me to keep my grade.

Thank you,
Eliza Hare

Success in piano this semester is dependent upon her touching every note of every assignment every day, with EMPHASIS on upcoming quiz items, not ONLY PRACTICING upcoming quiz items. Every. Single. Day. Not just the day before something is due.

Elise took the initiative to approach me before class this morning, saying she was very behind. When asked, she admitted she was behind in other classes as well, but mostly piano. She was having trouble with the class at the beginning of the semester, then she broke her ankle a few weeks ago and has missed class (excused) and gotten further behind since then. I suggested that she identify which parts of the exam she felt best about, and focus on doing her best in class, and we would talk afterwards.

During class, there were class performances of solo repertoire (ungraded) and accompaniments (ungraded), as well as an on-headset quiz over prepared readings (graded). Elise chose not to participate in the ungraded performances, and I excused her from taking the quiz because it was obvious she was grossly unprepared and I thought the time would be better spent discussing her future.

Elise, of her own accord, said that she was in so deep of a hole she didnt know if she could dig herself out, and mentioned dropping the course. I reminded her that the OCU policy is to remain enrolled unless given special permission (as is in the course syllabus). I told her it was mathematically possible for her to pass the course, but she would need to make some drastic changes in her practice habits, and likely spent Spring Break completely committed to practicing piano.  


Several times today, she expressed concern that her recently broken ankle was causing her difficulties, with doctors appointments and otherwise affecting her practice schedule. I reminded her that she wasnt doing well before that. 

She also mentioned that she might need to have surgery on her ankle after Spring Break, which could cause her to fall further behind. I encouraged her to talk to her advisors and other faculty members to get ideas on how to keep from falling behind, and prepare herself for not being 100% after Spring Break. I think she could use some help in this area (whatever help might mean in this situation).

As with all students, I encouraged Elise to focus on short, attainable practice goals, and to practice for no longer than 20 minutes at a time, but for several practice sessions a day. I also told her I was submitting a second early warning report.

Noah has missed many classes this semester, and missed Exam 2 Day 2. He has spoken with me twice about how he is changing his school and major, leading to him having difficulty focusing in class. Noah has always been pleasant and respectful when speaking with me, but he does need to actually show up and complete the material.

I told Noah that his best option is to do so well on the final exam that I can easily excuse some of his absences and eliminate some of the unexcused absence grade penalties. I was very clear that this wasn't a promise, but that it is a much more effective argument to *actually* change course with better attendance and exam preparation, rather than *promising* change will happen in the near future.

Alison missed Exam 2 Day 1 (Tues. 3/6) entirely, and only prepared partial components for Exam 2 Day 2 (Thurs. 3/8). 

I am unsure as to how to proceed. Although I try and refrain from making judgments about students, I have strong suspicions that Alison is not putting forth much effort, as a way of softening the blow if she doesn't play well.

As a general rule, I think Alison is completely capable of performing the material, and seems to have innate musicality that I enjoy hearing when she has the notes and rhythms learned. However, I have also noticed that she tends to memorize easily and is frequently playing from memory rather than reading from the score. I suspect that she is having difficulty making the leap from playing by ear, to reading from a score. Many of the assignments that she *does* play have mislearned figures, and what I call "Alison's arrangement of the assignment" rather than the assignment itself.

I have also noticed that Alison does not make good use of class time (playing while I am speaking, talking during freely structured class time, and generally being unprepared) and then seems to want to meet outside of class or get extra help. She seems to be setting up a situation where I am unwilling/unable to help her, when I am frequently offering her time/individual attention in class and she either declines it or is unable to make good use of the opportunity due to poor study skills.

I'm not personally familiar with the details of Josh Lewis's previous class piano experience, but I know he has a lengthy history.

Josh needs to complete this class with a C or above to meet his MUED minimum grade requirement, and he is not currently doing so. The final exam is worth 40% of his final grade, and it is definitely mathematically possible for Josh to meet his minimum grade requirement! However, he will need to make a significant change in his trajectory and I'm not convinced he is headed in that direction.

I try to avoid making judgment about students' motivations, but Josh seems to be a clear example of "not really trying" so that he has an excuse when he doesn't perform well. 

A recent specific example: Josh repeatedly tells me that he isn't interested in this class because he doesn't see its practical application in his degree program or anticipated occupation. I have been *very* open to him substituting different material for our standard curriculum, as long as he has it approved in advance. While Josh had a substitution accompaniment approved by me, whenever I went around to check on it and give them help, he always gave a humorous response and deflected actually playing much for me. He was absent the day before Exam 2, which is when the class was schedule to play their accompaniments in full, with their soloists, as a practice performance before the exam and to get some comments from me on their overall performance. Josh was absent that day. When he performed his accompaniment on the exam, it was *exceedingly* under tempo, to the point of affecting the meter, which is something he and I have previously discussed, although I'm not sure if we discussed it with this particular piece. He also left out the left hand almost entirely; although he claims he "played 50% of the notes!" I can give more details on this exchange if needed, but I think it is clear that this is neither the attitude nor the behavior of someone who *desperately* needs to bring up his grade in the class and has been given leniency in personalizing the curriculum to fit his personal interests.

I am very concerned that Josh will not meet his minimum grade requirements for this course.

To this he attributes poor attendance and performance academically. He has provided doctors notes that do indicate that he has been seen several times over the course of the semester, but there is never any indication that he be on restricted activity or away from work. His health concerns are not something that he has notified the university of. He is currently failing both of my classes (Aural Skills II and Music Theory II). In addition to failing aural skills based on his work, he is currently past the automatic failing point due to attendance. If there is a path he is able to pursue for medical withdraw or incomplete grades, that may be the only way I can accommodate him. Of course I do not want to see Marco held back in his studies/career, especially if there is a legitimate medical reason.
clarify_b: I thanked Marco for coming to talk to me and said open communication between himself, any physicians he is seeing, and the university/faculty would be key to navigating this difficult time. I made it clear that I cannot grant him a passing grade based on his current work, but that if he has medical reasons for an incomplete, I am happy to let him tackle the work when his health is stable. I also spoke with Marco at the outset of the semester about completing work (since it was an issue last semester), and at midterms (since he was failing). I have also been in contact with Dr. Michael Raiber and Dr. Ryan Robinson multiple times over the course of the semester since they have strong relationships with Marco.
